<DOC><DOCNO> AP891211-0210 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-12-11-89 0855EST</FILEID><FIRST>a a BC-History Adv18   12-11 0389</FIRST><SECOND>BC-History, Adv18,0410</SECOND><HEAD>$adv18</HEAD><HEAD>For Release Monday, Dec. 18</HEAD><HEAD>Today In History</HEAD><BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE><TEXT>   Today is Monday, December 18, the 352nd day of 1989. There are13 days left in the year.   Today's highlight in history:   On December 18, 1865, the 13th Amendment to the U.S.Constitution, abolishing slavery, was declared in effect.   On this date:   In 1737, the most renowned violin-maker in history, AntonioStradivari, died in Cremona, Italy.   In 1787, New Jersey became the third state to ratify the U.S.Constitution.   In 1813, the British took Fort Niagara in the War of 1812.   In 1915, President Woodrow Wilson, widowed the year before,married Edith Bolling Galt.   In 1956, Japan was admitted to the United Nations.   In 1957, the Shippingport Atomic Power Station in Pennsylvania,the first nuclear facility to generate electricity in the UnitedStates, went on line. In 1969, 20 years ago, Britain's Parliamentpermanently abolished the death penalty.   In 1972, the United States began its heaviest bombing of NorthVietnam to date during the Vietnam War.   In 1980, former Soviet Premier Alexei N. Kosygin died at age 76.(His death was not officially announced for two days.)   In 1985, the UN Security Council unanimously approved aresolution condemning ``all acts of hostage-taking and abduction.''   In 1987, Pakistani opposition leader Benazir Bhutto was marriedin a traditional Islamic ceremony to businessman Asif Ali Zardari.   Ten years ago: The Vatican censured the Rev. Hans Kung, aleading liberal theologian, declaring him guilty of heresy andbarring him from teaching.   Five years ago: Speaking to members of the British Parliament,Kremlin official Mikhail Gorbachev called for a ``breakthrough topeace,'' saying the Soviet Union was prepared to make radical armscuts if the United States and its allies were to go along.   One year ago: PLO chairman Yasser Arafat met in Cairo withEgyptian President Hosni Mubarak to discuss how to continue themomentum gained by the first United States-PLO dialogue.   Today's Birthdays: Actor Ossie Davis is 72. Former AttorneyGeneral Ramsey Clark is 62. Rock star Keith Richards is 46. Movieproducer-director Steven Spielberg is 42. Movie reviewer LeonardMaltin is 39.   Thought for Today: ``Friendship is an art, and very few personsare born with a natural gift for it.'' _ Kathleen Norris, Americanauthor (1880-1960).</TEXT><NOTE>End Advance for Use Monday, December 18</NOTE></DOC>